04215nam a22006255i 9781487595869DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191983onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875958697 a10.3138/97814875958692doi  a(DE-B1597)513688  a(OCoLC)1091659945  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aLIT0041902bisacsh1 aGinsberg, Warren , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Cast of Character :bThe Representation of Personality in Ancient and Medieval Literature /cWarren Ginsberg. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1983  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Idea of Character in Ovid: The Amores -- t2. The Representation of Character in Ovid: The Metamorphoses -- t3. Literary Typology and the Medieval Idea of Character -- t4. Boccaccio's Characters and the Rhetorical 'Disputatio in utramque partem' -- t5. The Cast of Character: Chaucer and the Conventions of Originality -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is concerned with the idea of character and the methods of representing it in ancient and medieval narrative fiction, and shows how late classical and medieval authors adopted techniques and perspectives from rhetoric, philosophy, and sometimes theology to fashion figures who define not only themselves but also their readers. Ginsberg first tests Ovid's concept in the Amores and the Metamorphoses against the conventions of classical tradition and shows how, although Ovid's idea of character did not change, his technique grew more subtle and complex as his art matured. Ginsberg then employs the methods of biblical exegesis to show how medieval characters – Gottfried's Tristan, Dante's Farinata, Chrétien's Yvain – both exist as themselves and point to characters beyond themselves, gaining depth and resonance because we see them in this perspective. Perspective is also a distinguishing quality of the maturing of Boccaccio's art. In the early works his characters seem to be little more than positions in a debate, but as he grew more skilful the strict formalism of binary oppositions gave way to the complexity of experience characteristic of the 'probably true' and culminating in the hundred perspectives of the Decameron. In Chaucer's Canterbury Tales the pilgrims are both typical and individual, twice-formed by the tale and by the frame. A character acts, and the reader forms expectations of his acting and in the process 'character,' the abiding glory of medieval literature, is created.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148759586940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487595869423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487595869.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK